snippet.textOriginal: Hey Jeff! Huge fan! I had a question that I hoped you or your team could address. I love your videos and your products. You stay on my phone while I am in the gym, as well as my gym partners.  We both have cursed you more than once after a rough set! My question is on nutrition and diet. I am having some trouble with regard to maintaining mass while getting leaner. I am 30 years old, am about 5'11, and started my diet at around 215 lbs. Now about 4 months later, I am around 175 to 179.  I try and stay around 1800 cals a day and try and run a mile 5 days a week and lift heavy 5 days a week. I am not getting any weaker as far as I can tell. I feel great and am around 13% body fat now. My issue is how to retain and gain more muscle mass without losing the leanness (if that's a word). I know you're not a believer in bulking and cutting, but what do I need to do to add more mass safely? I hope all is well with you and yours.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm glad he brought that up. so many guys think bench press is the pinnacle of testing strength. It has so much to do with physics and range of motion. A guy with short arms and a barrel chest will, of course, be able to press up more weight than a guy with long arms and a lean build. To each their own but I use a combination of resistance bands and free weights. I think bars, in the long run, cause more damage than benefit.
